For being willing to receive the Messias with all joyfulness, tri- umph, and affection of mind (for by calling him the Son of David, it is plain they took him for the Messias), they had no way to express a more ardent zeal and joy at his coming, than by the solemn procession of that feast. They have the Messias before their eyes ; they expect great things from him3 and are therefore transported with excess of joy at his coming.
